# .dockerignore — what NEVER enters the Docker build context.
#
# `docker build .` first packs the whole directory and ships it to the engine
# (on Docker Desktop the engine lives in a WSL VM, so this is a genuine copy
# across a VM boundary, not a local path lookup). Only then can COPY pick
# files out of it. Two things go wrong without this file:
#
#   1. Speed: .venv/ alone is hundreds of MB that would be copied on EVERY
#      build, before a single instruction runs.
#   2. Safety: the builder stage does `COPY . .`, so anything left in the
#      context can end up inside an image that gets pushed publicly to GHCR.
#      The dev vector store, the git history, and any local .env must not.
#
# Same syntax as .gitignore, but a SEPARATE concern: .gitignore answers "what
# is source?", this answers "what does the image build need?". Tests are
# tracked in git yet excluded here — the image doesn't run them.

# --- Large local state (regenerable; belongs on a volume, not in an image) ---
.venv/
venv/
chroma_db/
corpus/
build/
dist/
*.egg-info/

# --- Secrets: the API key reaches the container via the environment only ---
.env
.env.*

# --- Version control + CI metadata (not needed to build the app) ---
.git/
.github/
.gitignore

# --- Caches ---
__pycache__/
*.py[cod]
.pytest_cache/
.mypy_cache/
.ruff_cache/
.cache/
.huggingface/

# --- Dev-only files ---
tests/
.claude/
.vscode/
.idea/
*.md
!README.md

# README.md is un-ignored above because pyproject.toml declares
# `readme = "README.md"`; the wheel build fails without it.

# --- Docker's own files (changing them must not invalidate COPY layers) ---
Dockerfile
.dockerignore
docker-compose.yml
